    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "390f3e56e2a069b1",
      "text": "Vilém Flusser, [[Vom Subjekt zum Projekt]]: Menschwerdung, 1994, Schriften / Vilém Flusser, 3 (Bensheim und Düsseldorf: Bollmann, 1994), p. 201–202."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b4b8eca8301aa7cc",
      "text": "If we are sincere, we must confess that we condescend when we classify \"Homo sapiens sapiens\" as a kind of anthropoid. This is a (German) sentence that just cries out to be taken at its word. From where do we let ourselves down, if we confess sincerely? From the treetops in which we nest as anthropoids. And what do we do when we sincerely confess? [⇒ [[Sincerity]]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0fe886ceb3ba2bc3",
      "text": "We stand on our feet, head up, and let our hands dangle. Hence the (German) phrase, taken at its word, says: If we classify \"Homo sapiens sapiens\" as a type of anthropoid, we have previously lowered ourselves from the treetops and must therefore now confess sincerely. If one takes this word for word seriously (suppressing the laughter), one comes to the conclusion what existentially distinguishes us from chimpanzees – because the zoological differences between us two are not very considerable: The chimpanzee is in contrast to us not condescending enough (in old German: not lowly enough) to have to confess sincerely enough that he is an anthropoid. The chimpanzee is not sufficiently lowly to be considered as a candidate for becoming human. He is reluctant to condescend, and when he does, he is somewhat insincere about it. The chimpanzee hands, which are stretched out to us in the zoological garden through the cage bars, do not try therefore to hash after the possibility \"human being\", but after us, which we are for the time being its cousins."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6916a46aec43d011",
      "text": "The question which inevitably arises here is: How did it come then, \"in illo tempore\", and then again and again, whenever a baby is born, so far that baseness changes into sincere confession, so that our hands, which resemble the chimpanzee hands so much, act so completely unchimpanzee-like? This is the question from which any anthroplogy should start, especially since we know how closely we are related to the chimpanzees. In the zoological garden the animals in their cages are not classified according to species, genus, class and so on. Rather, we walk around as if we don't belong there, and then suddenly we stop in front of the chimpanzee cage. (Something quite different, but equally embarrassing, can happen to one in the aquarium in the face of cephalopods). This stubbing before the smacking chimpanzee grin, this disgust, which attacks us thereby before ourselves (and against which we fight momentarily), is this not about the moment, at which every anthropology (every talk of the human being) starts? But unfortunately one cannot approach this origin from Homonid in Homo, because there is no such thing as \"origin\". Logically there should be something like that, but there is not. One must proceed from this illogicality of the original becoming man."
    },
