      "type": "edit",
      "id": "b4b8eca8301aa7cc",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b4b8eca8301aa7cc",
        "text": "If we are sincere, we must confess that we condescend when we classify \"Homo sapiens sapiens\" as a kind of anthropoid. This is a (German) sentence that just cries out to be taken at its word. From where do we let ourselves down, if we confess sincerely? From the treetops in which we nest as anthropoids. And what do we do when we sincerely confess? We stand on our feet, head up, and let our hands dangle. Hence the (German) phrase, taken at its word, says: If we classify \"Homo sapiens sapiens\" as a type of anthropoid, we have previously lowered ourselves from the treetops and must therefore now confess sincerely. If one takes this word for word seriously (suppressing the laughter), one comes to the conclusion what existentially distinguishes us from chimpanzees - because the zoological differences between us two are not very considerable: The chimpanzee is in contrast to us not condescending enough (in old German: not lowly enough) to have to confess sincerely enough that he is an anthropoid. The chimpanzee is not sufficiently lowly to be considered as a candidate for becoming human. He is reluctant to condescend, and when he does, he is somewhat insincere about it. The chimpanzee hands, which are stretched out to us in the zoological garden through the cage bars, do not try therefore to hash after the possibility \"human being\", but after us, which we are for the time being its cousins."
