        "text": "The question which inevitably arises here is: How did it come then, \"in illo tempore\", and then again and again, whenever a baby is born, so far that baseness changes into sincere confession, so that our hands, which resemble the chimpanzee hands so much, act so completely unchimpanzee-like? This is the question from which any anthroplogy should start, especially since we know how closely we are related to the chimpanzees. In the zoological garden the animals in their cages are not classified according to species, genus, class and so on. Rather, we walk around as if we don't belong there, and then suddenly we stop in front of the chimpanzee cage. (Something quite different, but equally embarrassing, can happen to one in the Aquari um in the face of cephalopods). This stubbing before the smacking chimpanzee grin, this disgust, which attacks us thereby before ourselves (and against which we fight momentarily), is this not about the moment, at which every anthropology (every talk of the human being) starts? But unfortunately one cannot approach this origin from Homonid in Homo, because there is no such thing as \"origin\". Logically there should be something like that, but there is not. One must proceed from this illogicality of the original becoming man."
